idi falls $4bn into the red. Hedge funds back away from Binance after regul=
atory assault. Sri Lanka to Repay $1 Billion Bond, Ending  Default Threat.=
=C2=A0Citadel Securities Fined by Finra for  Trading Ahead of Clients. Cred=
it Suisse  Settles Spying Case With Ex-Wealth Chief Khan. Jeremy Grantham=
=E2=80=99s Firm Says Stocks Are Overpriced and  Social Media Is Wrong. Elon=
 Musk says Tesla caused two-thirds of his personal and professional pain. J=
eff Bezos' 18-year-old space-flight companion reportedly told him he had ne=
ver bought anything from Amazon before. =E2=80=9CFor Romania, the broadcast=
er used an image of Count Dracula.=E2=80=9DIf you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=
=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subs=
cribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Blo=
omberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] That is, (wealth in year n+1) =3D (weal=
th in year n) x (1.05), while (debt in year n+1) =3D (debt in year n) + ($3=
 million). Or (wealth in year n) =3D ($100 million) x (1.05^n), while (debt=
 in year n) =3D ($3 million) x n. If you divide the latter by the former yo=
u get a maximum of about 22.61% in around year 20; then it starts declining=
. Obviously this math is dumb and unrealistic: You will owe interest on the=
 debt, and your expenses will grow=C2=A0with inflation; it is too cute to a=
ssume that your debt grows linearly while your assets grow exponentially. (=
Also the assets can go down.) Still.
