<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Buy borrow die</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could have a dumb oversimplified m=
odel that goes like this:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding=
-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In the o=
lden days, rich people invested their money in stocks and bonds. They wante=
d cash flow from those stocks and bonds, money that they could live on with=
out spending principal. So the stocks and bonds produced cash flows. Invest=
ment-grade bonds paid interest, blue-chip stocks paid dividends, and their =
rich owners used the interest and dividend payments to finance their lifest=
yles.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In modern days, rich people =
still invest their money in stocks and bonds, but they have discovered the =
concept of tax efficiency. Dividends and interest payments are taxable; if =
you have $100 million of wealth,=C2=A0it earns 5% a year in interest and di=
vidends, and you pay a 40% tax rate, then in a=C2=A0year you=C2=A0will pay =
$2 million of taxes and be $3 million richer. You=E2=80=99d prefer not to p=
ay the taxes.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So it is no longer p=
articularly expected that good stocks will pay large, or any, dividends: Co=
mpanies retain earnings to reinvest in growth (rewarding their shareholders=
 with capital appreciation rather than dividends), or if they want to retur=
n cash they do it via tax-efficient buybacks rather than dividends.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Meanwhile the interest rates on bonds are=
 really low. This is more of a macroeconomic thing than a tax-efficiency th=
ing, honestly, but it=E2=80=99s worth noting.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">If you have $100 million of wealth and it appreciates by 5% per=
 year without paying out any cash, then in a=C2=A0year you will pay no taxe=
s and be $5 million richer. Better!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">How do you pay for your lifestyle? Well, if you have $100 million, you ca=
n pretty easily borrow money secured by your portfolio. If you borrow $3 mi=
llion a year (what we assumed you were taking home under the old system) an=
d your wealth keeps compounding at 5% per year, you will never borrow more =
than about 23% of the value of your holdings.[1] A bank should be fairly co=
mfortable lending you 23% of the value of your portfolio of stocks and bond=
s, since you=E2=80=99re rich.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Borr=
owing money is not <em>income</em>, so you don=E2=80=99t pay taxes on it.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">And you=E2=80=99ll pay very low int=
erest on this borrowing (see point 4).</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">It is just a more efficient way to extract spending money from wealth. (T=
his model is sometimes called =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/24559660.263121/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy=
9idXktYm9ycm93LWRpZS1ob3ctcmljaC1hbWVyaWNhbnMtbGl2ZS1vZmYtdGhlaXItcGFwZXItd=
2VhbHRoLTExNjI1OTA5NTgz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad0d56b2" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">buy borrow die</a>,=E2=80=
=9D because if you die in step 9, that can further improve the tax efficien=
cy of the strategy.) It does require a change in the business model of bank=
s, though: Instead of principally being in the business of lending money to=
 people who don=E2=80=99t have money and need some, they are increasingly i=
n the business of lending money to people who have lots of money but don=E2=
=80=99t want to liquidate financial assets.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>So <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24559660.26312=
1/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvOGEzMjhhZjQtYjhmMi00OGM1LTgyYTktZDdkY=
zFjMzQ1ZTFj/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB08678371" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">here you go</a>:</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lending businesses of large US banks are doublin=
g down on wealthier customers, as well-to-do Americans borrow to buy second=
 homes, invest in the stock market and potentially lighten their tax bills.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The combined value of loans made by the we=
alth management arms of JPMorgan Chase, Bank of America, Citigroup and Morg=
an Stanley surpassed $600bn in the second quarter, up 17.5 per cent from a =
year earlier. This represented 22.5 per cent of the banks=E2=80=99 total lo=
an books, up from 16.3 per cent in mid-2017. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">This type of borrowing has been on the rise for more than a decade bu=
t the pace has picked up since the Federal Reserve cut interest rates in re=
sponse to the pandemic. For a two-year loan against liquid investments such=
 as stocks, wealth management clients can expect to pay a rate of about 1.4=
 per cent, according to bankers and advisers.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">=E2=80=9CRates are so remarkably low that they look at it as cheap=
 money,=E2=80=9D said Christopher Boyett, co-chair of the private wealth pr=
actice at law firm Holland &amp; Knight.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
e contrast with the banks=E2=80=99 consumer and corporate loan books is sta=
rtling. Wealth management loans at JPMorgan, Bank of America, Citi and Morg=
an Stanley have grown 50 per cent in the past four years, compared with onl=
y 9 per cent for their overall loan book.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">J=
PMorgan and Citi are now lending more to a small number of ultra-high net w=
orth clients than to their millions of credit card customers. A decade ago,=
 JPMorgan was lending five times as much to credit card customers as it did=
 to private clients. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Controversially, t=
he borrowings can also serve to lower taxes. Instead of selling assets to r=
aise cash =E2=80=94 and facing a capital gains tax bill =E2=80=94 high net-=
worth clients obtain funding by borrowing against the value of their invest=
ments.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe other way that these fa=
milies could get liquidity from these assets=C2=A0would be to sell them=C2=
=A0and that of course would have tax consequences and those would not be fa=
vourable,=E2=80=9D said Sabrena Silver, a partner at law firm White &amp; C=
ase.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a bank, it is =
better to lend people money equal to a fraction of the value of their portf=
olio of liquid financial assets than it is to lend them money that they=C2=
=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0have</em>. If they already have plenty of money, =
they are more likely to pay you back. Meanwhile=C2=A0if you are a rich pers=
on, it is better to get liquidity without paying taxes than to get liquidit=
y and pay taxes. Seems like a good trade for everyone?</p><table class=3D"h=
eader" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Credit scoring</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/24559660.263121/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY=
2xlcy9maWNvLXNjb3Jlcy1ob2xkLW9uLXRoZS1jcmVkaXQtbWFya2V0LWlzLXNsaXBwaW5nLTEx=
NjI3MTE5MDAzP21vZD1ocF9saXN0YV9wb3My/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9d3fa2ae" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">this</a> is t=
he sort of cute pat anecdote that banks love to publicize:</p><blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FICO is becoming a smaller factor in underwriti=
ng decisions at Citizens Financial Group Inc. When shoppers apply for its b=
uy-now-pay-later loans, the bank considers factors including the products t=
hey are buying, according to a person familiar with the matter. Fitness equ=
ipment, for example, is viewed as a sign of creditworthiness because it sug=
gests a positive change in the applicant=E2=80=99s behavior. By next year, =
the bank plans to use cellphone, cable and utility-payment information to h=
elp vet loan applicants, the person said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Yes, right, buying a Peloton on credit increases your debt-to-i=
ncome ratio but improves your credit because people who do group fitness cl=
asses don=E2=80=99t default on debt, fine, but if you=E2=80=99re going to b=
rag about this to journalists you=E2=80=99ve got to publicize the whole lis=
t. Fitness equipment is credit-positive; what else is positive? What=E2=80=
=99s negative? If you are financing a flat-screen TV, that=E2=80=99s bad, r=
ight?=C2=A0A nice suit is good? What about a boat? Are there =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0are=C2=A0there purchase types that correlate both with creditworthiness =
and also with race or gender? I feel like this discussion is=C2=A0cute and =
positive when it is limited to fitness equipment but you don't actually wan=
t to open up the box here.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s f=
rom an article about how the =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/24559660.263121/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9=
maWNvLXNjb3Jlcy1ob2xkLW9uLXRoZS1jcmVkaXQtbWFya2V0LWlzLXNsaXBwaW5nLTExNjI3MT=
E5MDAzP21vZD1ocF9saXN0YV9wb3My/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC9d3fa2ae" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">FICO Score=E2=80=
=99s Hold on the Credit Market Is Slipping</a>=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Big lenders are moving away from FICO, according =
to people familiar with the matter. Capital One Financial Corp. and Synchro=
ny Financial don=E2=80=99t use its scores for most consumer-lending decisio=
ns. They are becoming a smaller factor in some underwriting decisions at JP=
Morgan Chase &amp; Co. and Bank of America Corp.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">A key financial regulator, meanwhile, is encouraging banks to de-emph=
asize credit scores in an effort to expand access to affordable credit. And=
 housing-finance giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac are considering allowing=
 lenders to use other scores when evaluating mortgage applicants.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are a few reasons for the shift. Many lenders =
now review a wealth of new data and use it to refine their own proprietary =
scores that they say are better able to predict who will repay and who won=
=E2=80=99t. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For banks, one benefi=
t of their own scoring systems is their ability to tweak them when problems=
 arise. Several years ago, JPMorgan noticed that when borrowers transferred=
 their credit-card debt to a personal loan, their FICO scores often increas=
ed because the share of debt they carried compared with their cards=E2=80=
=99 spending limits had fallen, a person familiar with the matter said. But=
 the debt was still present in the form of a personal loan. The bank found =
a similar issue with its own credit score but was able to quickly fix it, t=
he person said. FICO said recent versions of its scores address this issue.=
=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On first principles you=
 might think that a bank is in the business of deciding whom to lend money =
to. It is weird to outsource that core decision to someone else, and sensib=
le to try to bring it back in-house and also differentiate yourself. Like, =
banks=C2=A0<em>should=C2=A0</em>try to compete with each other by making be=
tter credit decisions, lending to creditworthy borrowers that the rest of t=
he market misses and avoiding lending to risky borrowers that the rest of t=
he market loves. If you are a bank you should try to get better at the core=
 skills of banking.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The counterpoint is tha=
t banks are not always exactly in the business of lending money from their =
balance sheets and hoping to get paid back. Sometimes they=E2=80=99re in th=
e business of packaging loans and selling them, and there, being=C2=A0<em>r=
ight=C2=A0</em>is less important than being=C2=A0<em>standard:</em></p><blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FICO has a big advantage: Investors re=
ly heavily on the scores to decide whether to buy packaged-up consumer loan=
s. The scores are a common language of sorts, one that requires no time-con=
suming translation. Even lenders that don=E2=80=99t use FICO to make lendin=
g decisions tend to use them in loan securitizations.</p></blockquote>
