om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Chinese tutoring</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two notable facts about the People=E2=
=80=99s Republic of China are that (1) it has been communist for the last 7=
0 years and (2) it bans foreign investors from owning shares of certain sor=
ts of technology companies. Until like a month ago, everyone thought China =
was =E2=80=A6 kidding? Yes sure China is ruled by the Communist Party, but =
look at all the profits that were being made by Chinese capitalists. And ye=
s sure foreign investors aren=E2=80=99t allowed to own=C2=A0Chinese tech co=
mpanies, but a robust <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/24559660.263121/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjEtMDctMDcvb3duaW5nLWNoaW5lc2UtY29tcGFuaWVzLWlzLWNvbXBsaWNhdGVk/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB6941a226" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> =E2=80=9Cvariable interest entity=E2=80=9D structure</=
a> allowed foreign investors to=C2=A0<em>effectively=C2=A0</em>own shares i=
n profitable Chinese tech companies. It=E2=80=99s fine! In very broad strok=
es, investing in China was like investing everywhere else.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Things <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/24559660.263121/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjEtMDctMjQvY2hpbmEtYmFucy1zY2hvb2wtY3VycmljdWx1bS10dXRvcmluZy1maXJtcy1mc=
m9tLWdvaW5nLXB1YmxpYw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7bd939cf" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> are different now</a>:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">China unveiled a sweeping overhaul =
of its $100 billion education tech sector, banning companies that teach the=
 school curriculum from making profits, raising capital or going public.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Beijing on Saturday published a plethora of r=
egulations that together threaten to up-end the sector and jeopardize billi=
ons of dollars in foreign investment. Companies that teach school subjects =
can no longer accept overseas investment, which could include capital from =
the offshore registered entities of Chinese firms, according to a notice re=
leased by the State Council. Those now in violation of that rule must take =
steps to rectify the situation, the country=E2=80=99s most powerful adminis=
trative authority said, without elaborating.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">In addition, listed firms will no longer be allowed to raise capital via =
stock markets to invest in businesses that teach classroom subjects. Outrig=
ht acquisitions are forbidden. And all vacation and weekend tutoring relate=
d to the school syllabus is now off-limits.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>The regulations threaten to obliterate the outsized growth that made stock=
 market darlings of TAL Education Group, New Oriental Education &amp; Techn=
ology Group and Gaotu Techedu Inc. They could also put the market largely o=
ut of reach of global investors. Education technology had emerged as one of=
 the hottest investment plays in China in recent years, attracting billions=
 from the likes of Tiger Global Management, Temasek Holdings Pte and SoftBa=
nk Group Corp.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24559660.263121/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc=
2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQ5OTYyMC8wMDAxMTA0NjU5MjEw=
NjMwNzcvdGFsLTIwMjEwMjI4eDIwZi5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8acffdca" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
