idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">about Greensill Capital</a>, a =E2=80=9Csupply chain fin=
ance=E2=80=9D company that was notionally in the business of making short-t=
erm loans secured by its clients=E2=80=99 accounts receivable (or payable) =
but was actually=C2=A0in the business of making long-term unsecured loans a=
gainst its clients=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Cprospective=C2=A0receivables.=E2=80=9D=
 In basic receivables finance, a=C2=A0client would sell its products to its=
 customers on credit, Greensill would front the cash to the client, and Gre=
ensill would get paid back with interest a few weeks later when the custome=
rs paid. In prospective receivables finance, a client would think of a pote=
ntial customer and write down how much it wanted to sell to the customer, G=
reensill would lend it some money, and it would roll the money over every f=
